article.headline: Fairleigh Dickinson 76, Seton Hall 71
article.story: EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- If there were any expectations this season for Seton Hall under new coach Bobby Gonzalez, Fairleigh Dickinson may have ended them on Saturday. Bernell Murray hit two go-ahead free throws with 2:25 to play and Cameron Tyler added four straight points to lead Fairleigh Dickinson of the Northeast Conference to a stunning 76-71 victory, snapping a 10-game losing streak against the Pirates of the Big East. "It feels real good," longtime coach Tom Green said after Fairleigh Dickinson beat Seton Hall for the first time since Jan. 10, 1968. "It feels real good. This is our second Big East game this week and we had a long ride home from Providence the other night, so this is going to be a pleasant short ride home." This game between the two neighboring New Jersey schools was like night and day compared to Providence. The Friars opened a 55-26 halftime lead and coasted. The Knights (1-1) never trailed in this one by more than nine points. They won the game with clutch shooting (51 percent) and a solid second-half defense that limited Seton Hall (1-1) to seven field goals, including three in the final 12:22. The win wasn't Fairleigh Dickinson's first against a Big East school. They beat Providence in 1984, Green's second season with the Knights. The loss was just another sign that there is parity in college basketball, added Gonzalez, the former Manhattan coach who took over after Louis Orr was fired despite taking Seton Hall to the NCAA tournament. "You have to come out every game and play like the world is going to end," Gonzalez said. "We can beat anyone on our schedule, but anyone can beat us. We can't panic. It's the second game of the season. We have to try to get better and learn from it." Andre Harris had 21 points to lead the Knights, who held a 43-32 rebounding edge. Tyler added a career-high 19 points and Michael Peeples had 16. Peeples said the preseason predictions that Fairleigh Dickinson would struggle after losing its top three scorers motivated this year's team. "We had to let everyone know we had a lot of veterans coming back, who had been in big games, and just show them that we could step up, too, and win big games," Peeples said. Brian Laing had 25 to lead Seton Hall, but only eight came in the second half, when the Pirates were 7-of-31 from the field (22.6 percent). Jamar Nutter added 20 points before fouling out in the final minute. Highly touted freshman guard Eugene Harvey, who was benched for most of the first half, finished with five points and two assists. Down the stretch there were seven ties and nine lead changes. Murray hit two free throws to give Fairleigh Dickinson a 69-68 lead with 2:26 to play. Seton Hall had a chance to take the lead right back, but Nutter missed two free throws with 2:10 to go. Compounding the problem, he later fouled Tyler, who made two more from the foul line for a 71-68 lead. "I'm still thinking about them now," Nutter said of the free throws. "If I made them it puts us up one and I felt if we were up one the whole thing changes." Stan Gaines, who had 10 points, and Laing missed chances for Seton Hall on its next possession. Tyler then seemed to take the air out of the Pirates with a 15-foot jumper for a 73-68 lead with 1:08 to play. Harvey missed badly on a 3-pointer with about a minute to go and Manny Ubilla eventually pushed the Knights lead to 75-68 with two more free throws with 32 seconds left. Laing only made it close with a 3-pointer with 23 seconds left. "Today was a tough day for us," Gonzalez said. "We couldn't get over the hump." Seton Hall led by as many as eight points early in the second half, and was still up by five with 13:19 to go.
